The Eassons compiled “William Blake: Notes toward a Catalogue of the American Blake Foundation Research Library” (12 February 1977), iv, 62 pp., xerox. 3 It was to be revised for “publication in September 1977,” though so far as I know it never appeared. In addition to criticism and the prints from No Natural Religion and Songs, the most notable holdings of the foundation recorded there were: Ariosto, Orlando furioso (1783, 1785, 1791, 1799); Blair, The Grave (1808 [“Subscribers’ Copy. Original Boards; uncut” plus the “Trade issue”], 1813 folio and quarto); Boydell’s Graphic Illustrations of . . . Shakspeare [?1803]; Mrs. [A. E.] Bray, Life of Thomas Stothard, R.A. (1851), extra-illustrated to 10 volumes “by Joseph Francis Daly with 829 engravings and 69 leaves with 110 original drawings by Thomas Stothard,” including the plate Blake engraved for Chaucer (1782), plus a proof before letters; Bryant, A New System, . . . of Ancient Mythology (1774, 1776); Bürger, Leonora (1796); Darwin, Botanic Garden (1791, 1795, 1799); Enfield, The Speaker (1774 [i.e., 1780]); Flaxman, Iliad (1805) and Classical Compositions (1870); Fuseli, Lectures (1801);
1. Roger and Kay Easson in the Center for the Study of William Blake at Illinois State University, holding their copy of Night Thoughts. On the table before them are Blake Trust facsimiles and a copy of the life mask of Blake, and on the shelves behind are recognizable Gilchrist’s life of Blake and works apparently in Japanese. Source: Edward Bury, “Mysticism Surrounds Blake Display,” Daily Vidette (Normal, Illinois, c. September 1976). Photo by Steve Cardot, courtesy of the Daily Vidette.
Gay, Fables (1793, [1811]); Hartley, Observations on Man (1791); Hayley, Cowper (1803), Triumphs of Temper (1803), Ballads (1805), and Romney (1809); Hogarth, “Beggar’s Opera” (“1st published state, 1788; 4th published state [Heath]; One Copy, colored”); Lavater, Aphorisms (1788) and Essays on Physiognomy (1792 [i.e., ?1818, lacking vol. 5], 1810); Malkin, A Father’s Memoirs of His Child (1806); Rees, Cyclopædia, two sets, one with 73 fascicles out of 79, one with 77; Ritson, Select Collection of English Songs (1783); Salzmann, Gymnastics for Youth (1800); Scott, Poetical Works (1782); Shakspeare, Plays (Rivington, 1805) and 8 vols. (missing vol. 4) (1839); Stedman, Narrative (1796, 1806); Stuart and Revett, Antiquities of Athens, vol. 3 (1794); Virgil, Pastorals (1821); Wollstonecraft, Original Stories (1791); Young, Night Thoughts (1797), two copies, one in “Original Boards uncut,” the other “disbound for exhibition.” 3. Roger wrote on 27 February 2007 that the catalogue was made “primarily for insurance purposes, since we were trusting the materials to movers.”

The American Blake Foundation also produced two more volumes (and proposed a third which has never appeared). These were the most important work it accomplished.
Roger R. Easson and Robert N. Essick, William Blake: Book Illustrator: A Bibliography and Catalogue of the Commercial Engravings. Volume I: Plates Designed and Engraved by Blake (Normal, Illinois, 1972);
. . . Volume II: Plates Designed or Engraved by Blake 1774-1796 (Memphis, Tennessee, 1979);
Volume III with plates designed or engraved by Blake 1797-1827 was never published.
